<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-083-430  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 083 430.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  March 6 1989 v6 n9 p 34(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FiberCom aims to extend reach of fiber-optic mainframe links.andO;(product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Higgins, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   FiberCom Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   FiberCom OptiChannel 7000 (Computer communications equipment)(product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionFiber OpticsChannel CapacityConnectivity.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   FiberCom's Fiber-Optic channel extender. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Steve HigginsandM;FiberCom Inc. plans to unveil next week a line of high-performance,fiber-optic channel extenders that company officials said can link disparatemainframes and peripheral devices over a distance as far as 10 kilometers.andM;Joining a growing fiber-optic channel-extender market currently led by IBMand Data Switch Corp., FiberCom's new OptiChannel 7000 series capitalizes onthe ability of fiber cable to raise the 400-foot limit of standard channelconnections using coaxial cable.andP;  Existing fiber-optic extenders aregenerally limited to six kilometers, company officials said.andM;The new channel extenders, which represent the first venture into mainframeconnectivity for the fiber-optic LAN products manufacturer, will be availablein versions for bridging distances of two, five or 10 kilometers, theofficials said.andP;  Each of the versions will in turn be offered withdata-transmission options of 750K bytes per second, 1.5M bytes per second or3M bytes per second.andP;  The different versions give users more options tochoose from as their bandwidth and distance requirements grow, officialssaid.andM;''This is the state of the art right now,'' said Frank Dzubeck, president ofCommunications Network Architects, a consulting firm in Washington.andP;  ''Butthe reason I was not too excited about it is because it is not FDDI,'' hesaid, referring to fiber distributed data interface, the emerging standardfor 100M-bps data transmission on fiber-optic cable.andM;In addition to linking mainframes to each other, the fiber-optic channelextenders can provide each mainframe with links to remote peripherals such astape drives, laser printers and computer-aided design terminals, officialssaid.andM;Each of the OptiChannel 7000 Series extenders, which FiberCom plans todemonstrate at next week's Interface '89 communications trade show in NewYork, supports IBM 43XX, 308X and 3090 mainframe processors.andM;FiberCom will begin shipping the products by June, officials said.andP;  Pricesrange from $18,000 (for an extender designed to provide 750K-byte-per-secondtransmission as far as two kilometers) to $45,000 (for the3M-byte-per-second, 10-kilometer model), a company spokesman said.andM;The firm plans to enhance its channel-extender line by the end of the yearwith models that employ laser-signal generators, officials said.andP;  Lasersignals enable fiber-optic cable to maintain signals for distances greaterthan 10 kilometers.andM;FiberCom, of Roanoke, Va., can be reached at (703) 342-6700.andO;</TEXT></DOC>